        <h3>How it started</h3> 
    </div>
    <div class="content">
        <p>I woke up March 15th very uncertain of what was going on. I had just worked the slowest Saturday night; all over the news is Covid-19. I had the next three days off and was glad because I didn’t want to be at work while this was going on. Over those three days I watched as the world shut down and before I could even understand it our Premier was shutting down all restaurants and bars effective immediately. I’ve been in the restaurant industry for 20 years and we always joked “RESTAURANTS DON’T CLOSE” and yet here I am watching every single one lock its doors.</p>
        <p>Prior to Covid-19 I had taken a couple of Python courses through Sheridan College. It was good but overall the online experience wasn’t quite what I wanted. Sure there were some assignments and some instructions but I felt like I was basically using Google to complete the work because the instruction just wasn’t quite enough. </p>
        <p>After that I stumbled across some videos about creating some simple websites, I followed along with the videos and made a couple HTML and CSS files and I really enjoyed it. This is when I decided this is what I’d really like to get into. I was creating some websites using notepad and thought it was just amazing. Now back to the middle of March, I knew I was about to have a lot of time on my hand as I was now officially laid off!!  I bought a Udemy course taught by Colt Steele, it came with great reviews so I bought the course for $20. </p>
        <p>April 4th I started the course and I was off to the races. I ploughed through the course within a month. This was my first mistake though, I did all the assignments and I made all the projects. However I did not retain enough of the knowledge I was learning. I was taking in so much information that after I was done a session at the computer I often would struggle with my own side projects.  </p>
        <p>If I could have done it differently I would have gone through the course the section by section twice. The first I should have been watching and taking notes and not coding along. The second time through was when I should have been coding along. I would have retained more but I was just so excited about creating websites and apps.</p>
        <p>The second mistake I made was not researching more about my Udemy class. It had been patched up to stay mostly up to date but I would quickly learn that all of the JavaScript syntax I had just learned would work but wasn’t the new way of coding. We were learning ES 5 … I had no idea that much of the syntax that was thrown at me over and over was now not used.</p>
        <h6>Hindsight is always 20/20</h6>    
        <div class="date">
            <p>March 15, 2020</p>
        </div>
