                 <h3>Zero to Mastery</h3> 
             </div>
             <div class="content">
                 <p>My Zero to Mastery course really opened my eyes to some of the outdated practices I had just been taught and had just been drilled into my brain. All those functions I created were now replaced with => and code was shorter and much nicer but it made it confusing after feeling like I had just learned an outdated syntax. I had known the course was a bit outdated and was warned about one section on JQuery as an example of it. JQuery is well past its prime according to most people online and while it’s a great knowledge to have, an entire section was dedicated to an underused library. </p> 
                 <p>Both my instructors Colt and Andrei both have a great way of making you feel like you should keep going even when you feel like you are just not getting it. That feeling of “I’m never going to remember all of this” was set aside a when they explain that every programmer feels like this at some point even as a seasoned programmer. </p> 
                 <p>Andrei from Zero to Mastery would constantly use examples like Bill Gates or Elon Musk at one point didn’t know what they were doing.</p> 
                 <p>The only real issue I have with the course is that the instructor using a Mac. The course is designed around him using that Mac and as a Windows user I have to follow a different set of videos and walk through performed by someone else. This other instructor was great don’t get me wrong but it makes you feel like you are not a part of the class when you have to venture off to find the Windows version.</p> 
                 <p>I am now starting to finish off the last 25% of the Zero to Mastery Web Developer course. I have got to touch on some React which is amazing so far. It is complicated though in comparison to some of what we have learned so far. </p> 
                 <p>Our final project is a facial recognition app. I am just starting my first watch in which I will take notes and go through without laying a finger on the keyboard. My hope is that I will be able to code along during my second time through with a greater knowledge of what’s coming next and how we get from point A to point B.</p>    
